## Appendix C: Learning Path for Marcel

This is a suggested sequence based on your background (CEO, content/strategy focus, limited coding depth):

### Week 1-2: Foundations (8-10 hours)

**Goal:** Understand the paradigm shift from autocomplete to agents.

**Read:**
- Part 1 of this guide (Foundations)
- Appendix A sources [1-10] (Claude Code basics)
- Appendix A source [78] (MCP announcement)

**Do:**
- Create your first Claude Code skill for something you do weekly (e.g., "analyze-competitor")
- Read your existing GrowthX CLAUDE.md and understand how context routing works

**Outcome:** You'll have built and used one skill. You'll understand why this matters.

### Week 3: Claude Code Deep Dive (6-8 hours)

**Goal:** Master SKILL.md structure and write better skills for GrowthX workflows.

**Read:**
- Part 2 (Claude Code Skills)
- Appendix A sources [11-20] (Claude Code advanced)
- Your own skills in /mnt/growthx-context/.cursor/skills/ (read 5 existing GrowthX skills)

**Do:**
- Rewrite 2 existing GrowthX skills using the best practices from Part 2
- Add better examples and context linking
- Document trigger descriptions clearly

**Outcome:** Your existing skills are now documented and optimized.

### Week 4: Cursor & Comparative Tools (4-6 hours)

**Goal:** Understand Cursor rules and how they compare to Claude Code.

**Read:**
- Part 3 (Cursor Skills & Rules)
- Appendix A sources [21-40] (Cursor deep dive)
- Your project's .cursorrules if you use Cursor

**Do:**
- Create a .cursorrules file for GrowthX (or update existing)
- Compare it to CLAUDE.md — notice the differences and similarities

**Outcome:** You can switch between Claude Code and Cursor fluently.

### Week 5: Prompt Engineering Intensive (8-10 hours)

**Goal:** Understand prompt engineering as a discipline.

**Read:**
- Part 5 (Prompt Engineering for Skills)
- Appendix A sources [41-60] (Prompt engineering core)
- One full research paper: Chain-of-Thought ([43]) or ReAct ([101])

**Do:**
- Take an existing GrowthX skill and improve its prompt using CoT (chain-of-thought)
- Test the improvement on 5 examples
- Document the before/after

**Outcome:** You'll understand why prompt quality matters.

### Week 6: Context Engineering (6-8 hours)

**Goal:** Learn to design knowledge bases and context for AI.

**Read:**
- Part 4 (Context Engineering)
- Appendix A sources [61-75] (Context engineering)
- GrowthX docs structure — why it's organized the way it is

**Do:**
- Add metadata tags to your docs/handbook
- Create an INDEX.md for your knowledge base
- Organize a category (e.g., /docs/products/) for optimal AI consumption

**Outcome:** Your knowledge base is now AI-friendly.

### Week 7: MCP & Integration (6-8 hours)

**Goal:** Understand MCP and how to connect external tools.

**Read:**
- Part 4 (MCP: What It Is and Why It Matters)
- Appendix A sources [76-100] (MCP core and servers)
- One MCP server implementation: GitHub or Notion

**Do:**
- Set up Claude Desktop with an MCP server (e.g., Notion)
- Build a simple MCP server wrapper around a tool you use (e.g., HubSpot, Slack)
- Test it from Claude Code

**Outcome:** You've integrated an external tool into Claude Code.

### Week 8: Agents & Multi-Step Workflows (8-10 hours)

**Goal:** Understand agent loops and build a multi-skill workflow.

**Read:**
- Part 6 (Agentic AI Patterns)
- Part 8 (Skill Architecture & Design)
- Appendix A sources [101-120] (Agent frameworks)
- ReAct paper deep dive

**Do:**
- Design a multi-step workflow for GrowthX (e.g., "Create Competitor Brief" = research + analyze + format + publish)
- Implement it using existing skills and new ones as needed
- Document the workflow in a skill

**Outcome:** You have a working multi-skill workflow.

### Week 9: Safety & Operations (4-6 hours)

**Goal:** Understand guardrails and how to operate AI safely at scale.

**Read:**
- Part 9 (Emerging Patterns & Future)
- Appendix A sources [196-205] (AI Safety & Security)
- GrowthX's audit logging practices (if they exist)

**Do:**
- Add error handling and logging to your existing skills
- Create a "test suite" for a skill (5-10 test cases with expected outputs)
- Document permission models for your MCP servers

**Outcome:** Your skills are production-ready.

### Week 10: Review & Synthesis (4-6 hours)

**Goal:** Synthesize what you've learned and create a GrowthX skills strategy.

**Read:**
- Re-read Part 1 (Foundations) — it will make more sense now
- Review Parts 2-9 — you'll notice connections you missed

**Do:**
- Create a "GrowthX Skills Strategy" document:
  - What's the vision? (e.g., "automate all research and delivery workflows")
  - What's the roadmap? (e.g., "Q1 2026: build 10 core skills; Q2: MCP integrations")
  - What's the team? (who owns which skills?)
  - What's the governance? (how do we version, test, deploy skills?)
- Present to your team
- Set up a quarterly review process

**Outcome:** Skills are now strategic, not tactical.

### Ongoing (Weekly)

- **Monday:** Review upcoming workflows and identify new skill opportunities
- **Wednesday:** Write or improve one skill based on feedback or new learnings
- **Friday:** Test your skills against real examples and iterate

### Reference Workflow (When You Build New Skills)

1. **Define the skill** — What's the trigger? What's the expected output?
2. **Write the prompt** — Use the patterns from Part 5 (few-shot, CoT, structured output)
3. **Get feedback** — Run it on 3-5 examples, iterate
4. **Document it** — Use the SKILL.md template from Part 2
5. **Add to your library** — Version it, link it from CLAUDE.md
6. **Share learnings** — Document what worked and what didn't for the team

### Shortcuts (If You're Pressed for Time)

- **Just want to write better skills?** Start with Part 2 + Part 5 (Claude Code + Prompt Engineering)
- **Just want to understand the landscape?** Read Part 1 + browse Appendix A
- **Just want to build production-ready skills?** Parts 2, 5, 8 + Appendix B (practitioners)

